kibook|part=Monsters|Ki-rin}}\n|PageNumber=57\n|OtherAppearances=''[[List of Dungeons & Dragons monsters (1974\u20131976)#TSR 2005 - Dungeons & Dragons Supplement III: Eldritch Wizardry (1976)|Eldritch Wizardry]]'' (1976),<ref>{{Citation | last =Gygax  | first =Gary  | author-link =Gary Gygax  | last2 =Blume  | first2 =Brian  | author2-link =  | title =Eldritch Wizardry  | place=  | publisher =TSR  | year =1976  | location =Lake Geneva, WI  | edition =1}}</ref> ''Monstrous Compendium Volume Two'' (1989),<ref>[[David Cook (game designer)|Cook, David]], et al. ''[[Monster Manual#2nd Edition Advanced Dungeons & Dragons|Monstrous Compendium Volume Two]]'' ([[TSR, Inc.|TSR]], 1989)</ref> ''Monstrous Manual'' (1993),<ref>Stewart, Doug, ed. ''[[Monster Manual|Monstrous Manual]]'' ([[TSR, Inc.|TSR]], 1993)</ref> [[Psionics (Dungeons & Dragons)|psionic]] variant of the ki-rin in ''[[The Complete Psionics Handbook]]'' (1991),<ref>[[Steve Winter|Winter, Steve]]. ''[[The Complete Psionics Handbook]]'' (TSR, 1991)</ref> third edition ''[[Oriental Adventures]]'' (2001)<ref>[[James Wyatt (game designer)|Wyatt, James]]. ''[[Oriental Adventures]]'' ([[Wizards of the Coast]], 2001)</ref>\n|Variants=\n|Description=Race of lawful good aerial creatures that will aid humans if the need to combat evil is great<br>An obituary to [[Gary Gygax]] specifically highlights the Ki-rin as an example of the way in which ''D&D'' embraces world culture and folklore.<ref>Jonathan Rubin, \"[http://www.slate.com/id/2185914/ Farewell to the Dungeon Master: How D&D creator Gary Gygax changed geekdom forever],\" ''Slate'' (March 6, 2008).</ref>\n}}\n{{D&D creature list\n|Name=[[Lich (Dungeons & Dragons)|Lich]]\n|PageNumber=61\n|OtherAppearances=[[List of Dungeons & Dragons monsters (1974\u20131976)#TSR 2003 - Dungeons & Dragons Supplement I: Greyhawk (1974)|Greyhawk set (1974)]]\n|Variants=\n|Description=Created with the use of powerful and arcane magic, formerly ultra powerful magic-users now non-human an